article.description:
Elton Brand had 17 points and 14 rebounds as
the Los Angeles Clippers surpassed last season's win total with a 95-78 win Sunday over the Cleveland Cavaliers.
article.headline: Brand leads Clippers to rout of Cavaliers
article.linkText: Clippers surpass last season's win total in rout
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Jeff McInnis opened his Sunday newspaper, looked at the NBA standings and wished things could be different for the Los Angeles Clippers. "Man, if we were in the Eastern Conference, we'd be in like second-place," McInnis. Not quite, but the Clippers are gaining ground in the West. Elton Brand had 17 points and 14 rebounds as the Clippers surpassed last season's win total with a 95-78 win Sunday over the Cleveland Cavaliers. Eric Piatkowski scored 17 points for the steadily improving Clippers, who are 32-31 with 19 games remaining. Los Angeles, which had seven players in double figures, went just 31-51 last year. "We're moving in the right direction," coach Alvin Gentry said. "We set a goal to make the playoffs at the start of the year and that's what we're working toward." The Clippers' win, coupled with Utah's loss at Houston, moved Los Angeles within 2½ games of the Jazz for the Western Conference's eighth playoff spot. McInnis finished with 10 points, nine assists and eight rebounds for Los Angeles. He had eight points and five rebounds in the third quarter, when the Clippers outscored the uninspired Cavaliers 25-14 to take control. Cleveland missed 11 straight shots in the period and didn't attempt its first free throw of the game until Bryant Stith got fouled making a layup with 2:56 left in the third. "I didn't like our energy level from anybody," Cavs coach John Lucas said. "It was totally unacceptable. That's not the kind of team I coach. It won't happen again." The Clippers dominated the Cavs on the boards, outrebounding Cleveland 59-34. The Cavaliers were without their top rebounder, starting forward Tyrone Hill, who sustained a mild concussion after banging heads with Milwaukee's Sam Cassell on Friday night. Hill is averaging 10.5 rebounds, but even he probably wouldn't have helped. "We can't miss Tyrone that much," Lucas said. Trajan Langdon led the Cavs with 17 points in 18 minutes. Andre Miller, who played 53 minutes in an overtime win at Milwaukee on Friday night, had six points and 11 rebounds in 30 minutes. "We laid an egg," Miller said. "When things didn't go our way, we kind of folded." Leading by six early in the third quarter, McInnis hit a jumper to ignite a 13-0 run by the Clippers. Piatkowski made a 3-pointer and hit a pair of technicals during the spurt when Miller and Lucas complained about the officiating. And even when the Clippers extended their lead, they didn't let up. They put away the Cavaliers to improve to 2-1 on a four-game Eastern trip that concludes Monday night at Minnesota. "We can't relax," McInnis said. "People get ready now for the Clippers." Lucas argued about several calls in the first half, and wondered aloud if his team would get to shoot a free throw before Stith finally was rewarded late in the third. After getting called for a technical in the third, Lucas spent much of the fourth quarter quietly staring at officials Blane Reichelt, Tom Washington and Derrick Collins. However, Lucas was most upset with his team's poor effort. "What I saw was, 'I'm stuck somewhere and I want to be at the beach somewhere,"' Lucas said. "I'm tired, too, but I'm a professional. I expect them to be professional." Game notes
McInnis was approaching his second career triple-double before being replaced with 10 minutes left. "That's OK," he said. "I'll trade that for a win." ... Miller's 10 assists gave him 659 this season, the fourth-highest total in team history. John Bagley's 735 assists in 1985-86 is the club record. ... Hill has been suffering from dizziness and is having trouble with his equilibrium, Lucas said. Hill, who missed the first 50 games this season with a bad back, will be re-evaluated Monday at the Cleveland Clinic. ... Lucas said C Chris Mihm will be activated before Wednesday's game against Detroit. Mihm has been out since Feb. 26 with a bruised knee. ... McInnis had eight assists in the first half, moving him past 1,000 in his career.
